nodes.bodyText:
My experience with this class was that it was some sort of primitive deadlock detector for cases where multiple locks were acquired on different, but concurrent, code paths.  That is, it was an attempt to enforce consistent lock ordering by preventing constructs like the following:
Thread A                   Thread B
--------                   --------
synchronized(lock1) {      synchronized(lock2) {
  . . .                      . . .
  synchronized(lock2) {      synchronized(lock1) {
    . . .                      . . .
  }                          }
}                          }

Where the lock acquisitions may happen in totally different methods, and thus not be obvious to a developer that they are introducing an inconsistent lock ordering.
I don't know if there are still such cases where the same set of locks are acquired on concurrent code paths.  If so, that would be the only reason I could see keeping this class around.

